\begin_layout Paragraph
Calculate how close the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ce{^{4}He}$
\end_inset

 particle comes to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ce{^{241}Am}$
\end_inset

 nucleus using the Berkeley Cyclotron.
 Compare this to the nuclear radii of the neuclei.
 Is there an overlap?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nuclear radius of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ce{^{241}Am}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated using a simple correlation.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{A}=\left(1.2\,\mathrm{fm}\right)A^{\nicefrac{1}{3}}=\left(1.2\,\mathrm{fm}\right)\left(241.\right)^{\nicefrac{1}{3}}=7.5\,\mathrm{fm}
\]

\end_inset

Then, to compare this to the approach of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 particle to the nucelus, we have to determine when the repulsion of the
 nucleus is larger than the kinetic energy imparted by the cyclotron.
 The kinetic energy imparted can be calculated knowing that the cyclotron
 gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 particle 
\begin_inset Formula $35\,\mathrm{MeV}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cunningham1959"

\end_inset

.
 This can be equated to the electrical charge energy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=\frac{1}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}}\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{r}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the charge of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 particle (
\begin_inset Formula $2+$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the charge of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ce{Am}$
\end_inset

 nucleus (
\begin_inset Formula $95+$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the permitivity of free space, and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the radius of interest.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r=\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi\epsilon_{0}U}=\frac{\left(2\cdot1.6\times10^{-19}\,\mathrm{C}\right)\left(95\cdot1.6\times10^{-19}\,\mathrm{C}\right)}{4\pi\left(8.85\times10^{-12}\,\mathrm{\frac{C^{2}s^{2}}{m^{3}kg}}\right)\left(35\,\mathrm{MeV}\right)}=7.8\times10^{-15}\,\mathrm{m}=7.8\,\mathrm{fm}
\]

\end_inset

which is close to the size of the nuclear radius, so the interaction can
 occur.
 
\end_layout

