\begin_layout Standard
The equation in the paper is reproduced below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Formula $R=10^{-26}\times\left(0.010/241\right)\times6\times10^{23}\left(\text{atoms of Am in target}\right)\times6\times10^{12}\left(\text{He}^{++}\text{ ions per second}\right)\cong1.5\times10^{6}\left(\text{atoms Bk}^{243}\text{formed per second}\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cunningham1959"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to write this symbolically, we should try to identify groups that
 correspond to calculateable quantities and match units.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\underbrace{10^{-26}}_{?}\times\underbrace{0.010}_{m_{Am}}\times\underbrace{\frac{1}{241}}_{\frac{1}{A}}\times\underbrace{6\times10^{23}}_{N_{A}}\times\underbrace{6\times10^{12}}_{?}
\]

\end_inset

From the given mass, and general knowledge of the atomic number and Avogadro's
 number, the three above groups can be determined, leaving two groups unidentifi
ed.
 The second group (
\begin_inset Formula $6\times10^{12}$
\end_inset

) has units similar to current, so a quick calculation of the number of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ce{He^{++}}$
\end_inset

 ions in a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\,\mathrm{\mu A}$
\end_inset

 beam shows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{\alpha}=\frac{I}{2\cdot e^{-}}=\frac{2\times10^{-6}\,\mathrm{A}}{2\cdot1.6\times10^{-19}\,\mathrm{C}}=6.25\times10^{12}\,\mathrm{\frac{He^{++}}{s}}
\]

\end_inset

showing that the second group is in fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 The final group, then, must be the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of interaction.
 Thus the final equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=P\frac{m_{Am}}{A}N_{A}I_{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset

In order to determine the cross section, we must relate this to a common
 definition of the reaction rate, namely
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\sigma N_{Am}I_{\alpha}=\sigma\frac{N_{A}\Delta x}{A}I_{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset

and equating this with above gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\sigma\frac{N_{A}\Delta x}{A}I_{\alpha}=P\frac{m_{Am}}{A}N_{A}I_{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=P\frac{m_{Am}}{\Delta x}
\]

\end_inset

and assuming the thickness to be a couple microns, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=10^{-26}\frac{0.010}{10.0\times10^{-4}}=1.0\times10^{-25}\,\mathrm{cm}=0.1\,\mathrm{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

